    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-11-12T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-11-12T00:00:00-05:00" n="117"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d117">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">
                    <persName corresp="#p_RFD1">Roosevelt</persName> Papers: Telegram
                    (paraphrase)</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_HWA2" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harriman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">President</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d117fn1">Sent to Washington by the United States Naval
                        Attaché, Moscow, via Navy channels.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-11-12">12 November
                            1943</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Personal and secret for the President from <persName corresp="#p_HWA2"
                        >Harriman</persName>.</p>
                <p>Unless you meet [<hi rend="italic">need?</hi>] us some place earlier, I plan to
                    be in Cairo by the 22nd with <persName corresp="#p_DJR1">Deane</persName>,
                        <persName corresp="#p_BCE2">Bohlen</persName>, Lt Mei[kl]ejohn and an army
                    interpreter Capt <persName corresp="#p_WHH1">Ware</persName>. None of us here
                    have heard of any senior Soviet staff officer who speaks English and <persName
                        corresp="#p_MVM1">Molotov</persName> could not think of one when I asked
                    him. It is not clear how many Soviet staff officers you <pb facs="0173" n="81"
                        xml:id="pg_81"/> expect in Cairo as your cable<note n="2" xml:id="d117fn2">
                        <persName corresp="#p_RFD1">Roosevelt</persName>’s message of November 8,
                        1943, to <persName corresp="#p_SIV1">Stalin</persName>, <hi rend="italic"
                            >ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_71">p. 71</ref>.</note> speaks of a
                    military representative in the singular and <persName corresp="#p_CC2"
                        >Churchill</persName>’s cable to <persName corresp="#p_SIV1"
                        >Stalin</persName>
                    <note n="3" xml:id="d117fn3">The cable quoted in <persName corresp="#p_CC2"
                            >Churchill</persName>’s telegram 500, November 10, 1943, to <persName
                            corresp="#p_RFD1">Roosevelt</persName>, <hi rend="italic">ante</hi>,
                            <ref target="#pg_78">p. 78</ref>.</note> expresses the hope that
                        <persName corresp="#p_MVM1">Molotov</persName> will bring a strong staff. It
                    would be helpful if you would cable me urgently so that I can clarify this point
                    to <persName corresp="#p_MVM1">Molotov</persName>.<note n="4" xml:id="d117fn4"
                        >On November 14, 1943, <persName corresp="#p_ML2">Mathewson</persName>, of
                        the White House Map Room, sent <persName corresp="#p_HWA2"
                            >Harriman</persName> a message, in <persName corresp="#p_SERJ1"
                            >Stettinius</persName>’ name, to the effect that no reply to this
                        telegram, or to <persName corresp="#p_HWA2">Harriman</persName>’s telegrams
                        to <persName corresp="#p_HHL1">Hopkins</persName> (see <hi rend="italic"
                            >post</hi>, <ref target="#pg_85">p. 85</ref>), was possible for the time
                        being, as the addressees were on a trip. <persName corresp="#p_ML2"
                            >Mathewson</persName> sent the three messages to Oran by pouch, for
                        delivery on the arrival of <persName corresp="#p_RFD1">Roosevelt</persName>
                        and <persName corresp="#p_HHL1">Hopkins</persName> there.</note>
                </p>
            </div>
        </body>
